<li id="cite_note-24"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.digitalhistory.uh.edu/historyonline/con_economic.cfm" class="external text" title="http://www.digitalhistory.uh.edu/historyonline/con_economic.cfm" rel="nofollow">Was slavery the engine of economic growth? Digital History</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25" title="">^</a></b> The Royal Navy itself may have contributed to Britain’s industrial growth. Among the first complex industrial manufacturing processes to arise in Britain were those that produced material for British warships. For instance, the average warship of the period used roughly 1000 pulley fittings. With a fleet as large as the Royal Navy, and with these fittings needing to be replaced ever 4 to 5 years, this created a great demand which encouraged industrial expansion. The industrial manufacture of rope can also be see as a similar factor.</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Barrington_Moore,_Jr." title="Barrington Moore, Jr.">Barrington Moore, Jr.</a>, <i>Social Origins of Dictatorship and Democracy: Lord and Peasant in the Making of the Modern World</i>, pp. 29-30, Boston, Beacon Press, 1966.</li>
<li id="cite_note-27"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFFoster2004">Foster, Charles (2004). <i>Capital and Innovation: How Britain Became the First Industrial Nation</i>. Northwich: Arley Hall Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0951838245" class="internal">ISBN 0951838245</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Capital+and+Innovation%3A+How+Britain+Became+the+First+Industrial+Nation&amp;rft.aulast=Foster&amp;rft.aufirst=Charles&amp;rft.au=Foster%2C+Charles&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.place=Northwich&amp;rft.pub=Arley+Hall+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0951838245&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Industrial_Revolution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> Argues that capital accumulation and <a href="/wiki/Wealth_concentration" title="Wealth concentration" class="mw-redirect">wealth concentration</a> in an entrepreneurial culture following the <a href="/wiki/Commercial_revolution" title="Commercial revolution" class="mw-redirect">commercial revolution</a> made the industrial revolution possible, for example.</li>
